One’s cultural experiences can
            can
          impact their ability and willingness for suicidality disclosure. Help-seeking behaviors are already low in individuals who suffer from suicidality (Mann et al., 
            2005
         ). Ethnic and racial minorities must also overcome what Yu et al. (
            2022
         ) describe as the “double stigma,” or the compounding experience of discrimination based on both racial identity and mental health diagnostic status. These researchers did observe that racial stigma increased Black adults’ perceived barriers to seeking mental healthcare. It is also important to note that medical mistrust, especially among the African American community given their historical mistreatment, impacts their willingness to seek mental healthcare to this day (Colvin et al., 
            2024
         ). Therefore, culturally competent clinicians must consistently recognize the systematic and individual barriers ethnically and racially diverse individuals must overcome to participate in formal assessments.
